to application code, but also to the

44
00:03:10,286 --> 00:03:14,435
data pipelines, database changes,
schemas, and machine learning models

45
00:03:16,797 --> 00:03:17,036
Right?

46
00:03:20,617 --> 00:03:25,137
so let's begin with why traditional
pipelines may break down, right?

47
00:03:25,656 --> 00:03:28,316
So there are three major problems.

48
00:03:28,417 --> 00:03:29,737
The first is latency.

49
00:03:29,917 --> 00:03:31,718
Latency simply means delay.

50
00:03:34,096 --> 00:03:39,057
any delay in data costs
you your business, right?

51
00:03:39,177 --> 00:03:44,617
So if a customer abandons a cart at
ten AM and the marketing team can only

52
00:03:44,677 --> 00:03:49,656
sees-- see the data the next day, like
in a whole batch-based processing, that

53
00:03:49,757 --> 00:03:53,737
business has lost the chance to respond
to that customer at the right moment.

54
00:03:54,816 --> 00:03:56,918
So the second problem is fragmentation.

55
00:03:57,457 --> 00:04:01,697
So marketing data comes from many
different systems: websites, mobile apps,

56
00:04:01,816 --> 00:04:07,218
Google Ads, Meta Ads, you name it, CRM
tools, email platforms, support platforms.

57
00:04:07,738 --> 00:04:10,357
Each system has its own format and timing.

58
00:04:10,876 --> 00:04:14,077
So trying to combine all of
this only through batch ETL

59
00:04:14,137 --> 00:04:15,457
becomes slow and difficult.

60
00:04:16,937 --> 00:04:18,677
The third problem is scalability.

61
00:04:19,356 --> 00:04:21,216
Marketing workloads are unpredictable.

62
00:04:21,557 --> 00:04:26,077
A flash sale, a festive campaign,
an influencer promotion, or a

63
00:04:26,177 --> 00:04:30,496
product launch can create huge
spikes in traffic all of a sudden.

64
00:04:31,337 --> 00:04:35,597
So one minute the website must be--
might be having normal traffic, five

65
00:04:35,657 --> 00:04:41,097
minutes later, thousands of customers are
clicking your website, browsing, adding

66
00:04:41,157 --> 00:04:43,657
cart, purchasing, all at the same time.

67
00:04:43,697 --> 00:04:46,137
So static infrastructure
cannot handle this well.

68
00:04:46,177 --> 00:04:49,957
So this is why we need
event-driven architecture, and

69
00:04:49,977 --> 00:04:51,817
it becomes all the more important

70
00:04:54,077 --> 00:04:58,337
So in an event-driven system, every
customer action is treated as an event.

71
00:04:59,217 --> 00:05:03,437
A page view is an event, a click is an
event, adding an item to a cart is an

72
00:05:03,498 --> 00:05:06,137
event, completing a purchase is an event.

73
00:05:06,777 --> 00:05:10,498
Each event is captured immediately
and sent through the data platform.

74
00:05:11,736 --> 00:05:16,937
So when a customer views a product, that
event can update a dashboard, refresh

75
00:05:16,977 --> 00:05:20,758
the customer's profile, or even help
the recommendation engine understand

76
00:05:20,796 --> 00:05:22,296
what the customer is interested in.

77
00:05:24,157 --> 00:05:28,678
When a customer clicks an offer, that
can be used as A/B testing, campaign

78
00:05:28,736 --> 00:05:30,537
measurement, and behavioral scoring.

79
00:05:31,518 --> 00:05:35,337
When a customer abandons a cart, they
can even trigger a recovery campaign.

80
00:05:35,377 --> 00:05:39,858
So instead of looking backward at what
happened yesterday, the businesses can

81
00:05:39,957 --> 00:05:42,217
act while the customer is still active

82
00:05:44,753 --> 00:05:44,953
Okay.

83
00:05:46,854 --> 00:05:49,634
So now let's talk about
the data storage layer.

84
00:05:49,953 --> 00:05:54,454
So a data warehouse such as Snowflake,
BigQuery, Redshift is like a very

85
00:05:54,593 --> 00:05:57,614
well-organized office filing cabinet.

86
00:05:58,313 --> 00:06:00,933
It's excellent for clean, structured data.

87
00:06:01,914 --> 00:06:05,654
So if, say, for example, a marketing
manager wants to ask what was our

88
00:06:05,713 --> 00:06:10,513
revenue yesterday, or which campaign
generated the most conversion, a data

89
00:06:10,574 --> 00:06:12,353
warehouse is a good place to answer that.

90
00:06:13,914 --> 00:06:18,534
Snowflake, for example, can store clean
marketing data and support dashboards.

91
00:06:19,973 --> 00:06:23,174
But again, marketing data is
not always clean and structured.

92
00:06:24,093 --> 00:06:28,854
Clickstream logs, raw app events,
product images, creative assets, customer

93
00:06:28,933 --> 00:06:34,393
journey data, all these sort of data
are messy and are semi-structured.

94
00:06:35,073 --> 00:06:37,154
So this is why data lake is useful.

95
00:06:38,053 --> 00:06:42,793
A data lake is a large storage area where
we can keep raw data in different formats.

96
00:06:43,654 --> 00:06:47,154
But if you only want to use a
data lake, it may not be fast or

97
00:06:47,212 --> 00:06:49,712
organized for business dashboards.

98
00:06:50,453 --> 00:06:53,993
So this is why many organizations
are using a lakehouse approach.

99
00:06:54,953 --> 00:06:59,553
So a lakehouse will combine the best
of both worlds, so it gives us the

100
00:06:59,673 --> 00:07:04,092
flexibility of a data lake and the
analytical power of a warehouse.

101
00:07:05,113 --> 00:07:09,533
So for example, raw clickstream events
can be stored for future machine learning,

102
00:07:09,874 --> 00:07:14,194
while clean campaign and revenue data
can be queried quickly for dashboard.

103
00:07:16,233 --> 00:07:21,893
So the… in simple terms,
warehouse helps us report, the

104
00:07:21,993 --> 00:07:25,733
lake helps us store raw behavior.

105
00:07:25,793 --> 00:07:28,693
The lakehouse helps us report,
learn, predict, and improve

106
00:07:28,753 --> 00:07:30,693
from the same foundation.

107
00:07:30,773 --> 00:07:33,693
So now let's move on to
the streaming pipelines

108
00:07:37,757 --> 00:07:42,417
So at the center of many
real-time systems is Apache Kafka.

109
00:07:43,118 --> 00:07:46,457
So Kafka is like a live message highway.

110
00:07:46,657 --> 00:07:49,018
So every customer action
becomes a message.

111
00:07:50,058 --> 00:07:54,098
so for example, a customer viewed a
product, a customer abandoned a cart-

112
00:07:54,438 --> 00:07:56,897
cart, customer added item to a cart.

113
00:07:57,617 --> 00:08:01,037
So Kafka receives these messages
and sends them to different

114
00:08:01,098 --> 00:08:02,337
systems at the same time.

115
00:08:03,657 --> 00:08:09,337
One system may update real-time audience
segments, another system may update

116
00:08:09,357 --> 00:08:13,018
the recommendation engine, another
may trigger a marketing campaign.

117
00:08:13,038 --> 00:08:16,057
So the important thing there
is that these systems do not

118
00:08:16,137 --> 00:08:17,497
need to wait for each other.

119
00:08:18,198 --> 00:08:22,757
So Kafka allows many downstream systems
to consume same events independently.

120
00:08:23,837 --> 00:08:29,257
So on top of Kafka, stream processing
tools such as, Apache Flink, Spark

121
00:08:29,358 --> 00:08:34,457
Streaming, AWS, Kinesis process
the data while it is moving.

122
00:08:35,178 --> 00:08:40,037
So Kafka carries the events,
Flink or Spark Streaming

123
00:08:40,116 --> 00:08:43,337
processes the events, right?

124
00:08:44,337 --> 00:08:50,697
Snowflake or another warehouse stores
and analyzes the clean data, right?

125
00:08:52,718 --> 00:08:59,277
so this is where real-time audience
segmentation becomes very important

126
00:09:05,724 --> 00:09:10,765
So audience segmentation simply
means grouping customers based

127
00:09:10,865 --> 00:09:13,145
on who they are, what they do.

128
00:09:13,265 --> 00:09:17,365
So for example, our customers
who viewed shoes but did not buy,

129
00:09:18,204 --> 00:09:22,844
customers who added items to a cart,
customers who are active right now.

130
00:09:23,385 --> 00:09:26,964
So in real-time marketing, these
groups should be updated immediately.

131
00:09:27,625 --> 00:09:31,045
So if a customer abandons a
cart now, we do not want to add

132
00:09:31,084 --> 00:09:32,464
them to the segment tomorrow.

133
00:09:32,825 --> 00:09:35,285
We want the segment to be updated now.

134
00:09:36,824 --> 00:09:38,665
But this creates a technical challenge.

135
00:09:39,305 --> 00:09:44,165
So in a streaming environment, thousands
or even millions of customer profiles

136
00:09:44,305 --> 00:09:46,026
updates may arrive every second

137
00:09:48,650 --> 00:09:52,430
So the system cannot slowly
scan every customer one by one.

138
00:09:52,690 --> 00:09:55,710
It needs smarter ways to find
the right customers quickly.

139
00:09:56,290 --> 00:09:59,170
So this is where specialized indexes help.

140
00:09:59,750 --> 00:10:02,110
So let me explain this in a simple way.

141
00:10:02,270 --> 00:10:06,990
So an index is like the
index at the back of a book.

142
00:10:07,390 --> 00:10:10,830
So instead of reading the whole
book, you go to the index and

143
00:10:10,930 --> 00:10:12,470
quickly find the page you need.

144
00:10:13,610 --> 00:10:17,070
In real-time segmentation, we
need advanced indexes because

145
00:10:17,080 --> 00:10:18,670
the questions are more complex.

146
00:10:19,250 --> 00:10:20,970
So first, we have inverted index.

147
00:10:22,230 --> 00:10:25,650
an inverted index is keeping
like a ready-made list.

148
00:10:26,770 --> 00:10:29,990
One list may contain all
customers interested in shoes.

149
00:10:30,390 --> 00:10:36,320
Another list may contain all customers
who clicked a, discount ad. So when the,

150
00:10:38,570 --> 00:10:43,870
marketing teams, hey, ask who are the
customers who are inter-interested

151
00:10:43,930 --> 00:10:48,850
in shoes and also clicked on the
discounted ad, the system does not

152
00:10:48,950 --> 00:10:50,970
check every customer individually.

153
00:10:51,510 --> 00:10:56,210
It rather compares these ready-made lists
and finds the matching customers quickly.

154
00:10:57,650 --> 00:10:59,610
Second, we have bitmap indexes.

155
00:11:01,370 --> 00:11:04,150
these indexes are a yes or no checklist.

156
00:11:05,470 --> 00:11:09,130
So for each customer, the system may
just track simple behavior flags.

157
00:11:09,910 --> 00:11:11,290
Clicked ad, yes or no?

158
00:11:12,030 --> 00:11:13,450
Added to cart, yes or no?

159
00:11:13,990 --> 00:11:15,150
Purchased, yes or no?

160
00:11:15,790 --> 00:11:19,410
So computers are extremely fast at
checking these yes or no patterns.

161
00:11:19,430 --> 00:11:26,570
So if the campaign, system asks, "Hey,
find everyone who clicked the ad, added

162
00:11:26,580 --> 00:11:31,250
to cart, but did not purchase," bitmap
indexes can answer that very quickly.

163
00:11:32,390 --> 00:11:35,330
Third, we have materialized views.

164
00:11:36,050 --> 00:11:39,890
A materialized view is like
preparing the answer in advance.

165
00:11:40,310 --> 00:11:44,450
So for example, marketing teams often
ask the same questions repeatedly.

166
00:11:44,790 --> 00:11:46,490
How many users abandoned carts today?

167
00:11:46,960 --> 00:11:48,970
Which campaign is driving
the most purchase?

168
00:11:49,450 --> 00:11:54,530
So instead of calculating the same
answer again and again from raw data, the

169
00:11:54,590 --> 00:11:57,629
systems keep a pre-computed result ready.

170
00:11:57,670 --> 00:12:01,270
So when the dashboard asks the question,
the answer appears almost instantly.

171
00:12:02,290 --> 00:12:07,970
So this is why, real-time marketing
analytics is not only a data

172
00:12:08,010 --> 00:12:12,470
engineering problem, it is also a
data-based architecture problem.

173
00:12:12,550 --> 00:12:15,690
So we need the right storage,
the right streaming pipeline,

174
00:12:15,990 --> 00:12:17,470
the right indexing strategy.

175
00:12:17,950 --> 00:12:19,930
But technology alone is not enough.

176
00:12:20,430 --> 00:12:23,740
This is where DataOps becomes essential.

177
00:12:26,822 --> 00:12:31,222
the same principles that made DevOps
effective for software delivery must

178
00:12:31,262 --> 00:12:33,182
be applied to data platforms too.

179
00:12:33,822 --> 00:12:36,952
So in software DevOps, we
use version control for code.

180
00:12:37,602 --> 00:12:42,102
In DataOps, we need version control
for schemas and pipeline definitions.

181
00:12:43,722 --> 00:12:46,002
in DevOps, we used automated testing.

182
00:12:46,582 --> 00:12:52,242
In DataOps, we need a automated data
quality validation and regression testing.

183
00:12:53,502 --> 00:12:56,942
In application delivery,
we use CI/CD pipelines.

184
00:12:57,722 --> 00:13:02,542
In database analytic environments, we
need CI/CD for database migrations.

185
00:13:03,962 --> 00:13:06,442
In software operations,
we monitor services.

186
00:13:06,862 --> 00:13:11,382
In DataOps, we monitor
pipelines, freshness of data,

187
00:13:11,482 --> 00:13:13,502
schema failures, consumer lag.

188
00:13:14,742 --> 00:13:19,042
This matters because real-time systems
have no overnight maintenance window.

189
00:13:19,262 --> 00:13:20,722
Data is always moving.

190
00:13:21,462 --> 00:13:26,342
Customers are always interacting,
so the system cannot simply, stop

191
00:13:26,422 --> 00:13:28,232
because the schema needs to be changed.

192
00:13:28,962 --> 00:13:33,722
So that leads us to schema
evolution without downtime.

193
00:13:35,582 --> 00:13:39,242
So in a streaming system, we
cannot stop everything at midnight

194
00:13:40,122 --> 00:13:41,442
and make the change manually.

195
00:13:41,522 --> 00:13:45,582
So data, as I said, is always
moving, customers are always active.

196
00:13:46,082 --> 00:13:50,162
So this is why schema evolution
must happen without downtime.

197
00:13:51,242 --> 00:13:55,602
A safe way, approach is
expand, migrate, and contract.

198
00:13:57,802 --> 00:14:01,522
so first we expand by adding
a new field in a safe way.

199
00:14:01,842 --> 00:14:04,882
Then we might migrate producers
and consumers gradually.

200
00:14:05,682 --> 00:14:09,642
Finally, when the old version is
no longer needed, we remove it.

201
00:14:10,602 --> 00:14:14,892
So this sort of allows the system to keep
running while changes are introduced.

202
00:14:16,222 --> 00:14:18,722
a schema registry helps
enforce these rules.

203
00:14:19,082 --> 00:14:24,582
It prevents one team from accidentally
publishing a data format that

204
00:14:24,602 --> 00:14:26,162
breaks another team's pipeline.

205
00:14:29,342 --> 00:14:32,242
the same idea applies to
machine learning models, right?

206
00:14:33,582 --> 00:14:37,502
in marketing, machine learning models
may predict which customer is likely

207
00:14:37,542 --> 00:14:41,162
to buy, which product to recommend,
or which customer may abandon.

208
00:14:42,362 --> 00:14:47,342
customer behavior is constantly
changing, so models need retraining.

209
00:14:47,502 --> 00:14:52,542
But we cannot just replace a model
suddenly and hope it works, right?

210
00:14:58,305 --> 00:14:58,945
which is why,

211
00:15:01,045 --> 00:15:04,746
zero time downtime model
training is very important.

212
00:15:04,846 --> 00:15:10,906
So zero downtime model retraining allows
us new models to be trained in parallel,

213
00:15:11,165 --> 00:15:13,825
validated, and gradually introduced,

214
00:15:15,866 --> 00:15:19,325
monitored, and then promoted once stable.

215
00:15:19,386 --> 00:15:24,906
So a blue-green or canary deployment
strategy can shift traffic gradually

216
00:15:24,945 --> 00:15:28,626
from old model to the new model
while still monitoring performance.

217
00:15:29,586 --> 00:15:33,305
Auto ML can take this further
by automating the featuring--

218
00:15:33,506 --> 00:15:37,506
feature engineering, model
selection, hyperparameter

219
00:15:37,606 --> 00:15:40,406
tuning, and retraining cycles.

220
00:15:40,866 --> 00:15:45,165
So when drift is detected, retraining
can be triggered automatically,

221
00:15:45,445 --> 00:15:49,465
reducing drift to time, deployment
time from weeks to even hours.

222
00:15:51,226 --> 00:15:51,445
Okay.

223
00:15:54,465 --> 00:15:57,286
so now let's talk about scaling.

224
00:15:57,606 --> 00:16:00,506
So marketing workloads, like
I said, are spiky by nature.

225
00:16:01,125 --> 00:16:03,565
Reactive auto-scaling is often too slow.

226
00:16:04,026 --> 00:16:08,366
So inf-infrastructure only scales
after traffic has already surged.

227
00:16:08,545 --> 00:16:13,646
Users may experience slow dashboard,
delayed personalization, or

228
00:16:13,685 --> 00:16:15,146
even missed campaign triggers.

229
00:16:15,606 --> 00:16:19,425
So a better strategy rather
is prova- proactive scaling.

230
00:16:19,986 --> 00:16:24,846
For example, event ingestion rate
can act as a leading indicator.

231
00:16:24,965 --> 00:16:29,286
If the event bus starts receiving a
sudden surge in activity, that may

232
00:16:29,295 --> 00:16:33,136
predict incoming query load at the
warehouse or segmentation layer.

233
00:16:34,146 --> 00:16:39,045
The system can then scale
query infrastructure before

234
00:16:39,065 --> 00:16:40,325
the spike even reaches it.

235
00:16:41,045 --> 00:16:44,526
So the goal is not just to
survive peak load, the goal is

236
00:16:44,545 --> 00:16:49,026
to actually maintain consistent
latency throughout the peak load

237
00:16:51,209 --> 00:16:54,728
Observe- observability is
what makes this possible.

238
00:16:54,929 --> 00:16:57,269
So a batch job usually succeeds or fails.

239
00:16:57,829 --> 00:16:59,809
A streaming pipeline is more subtle.

240
00:17:00,629 --> 00:17:02,309
it can degrade gradually.

241
00:17:03,329 --> 00:17:08,668
Consumer lag increases, schema
failure rises, data quality erodes,

242
00:17:09,388 --> 00:17:13,329
model predictions drift, and by the
time a traditional alert fires, the

243
00:17:13,388 --> 00:17:15,249
business impact may already be visible.

244
00:17:15,729 --> 00:17:19,868
That is why streaming observability
needs to focus on leading indicators.

245
00:17:20,229 --> 00:17:26,089
So consumer lag tells us whether
processes are keeping up with ingestion.

246
00:17:26,670 --> 00:17:32,049
Schema failure rates reverse-- reveal,
upstream data quality issues before

247
00:17:32,089 --> 00:17:33,789
they corrupt downstream models.

248
00:17:34,408 --> 00:17:39,150
P99 query latency exposes
pressure on critical dashboards.

249
00:17:39,990 --> 00:17:46,629
Model drift metrics show when predictions
are no longer behaving as, expected

250
00:17:50,633 --> 00:17:55,053
in distributed systems, consistency
needs to be intentional.

251
00:17:55,812 --> 00:17:58,654
Not every marketing event
carries the same business risk.

252
00:17:58,934 --> 00:18:01,434
A misclick may be okay.

253
00:18:01,973 --> 00:18:04,933
A duplicate purchase record may not be.

254
00:18:04,973 --> 00:18:05,173
All right

255
00:18:08,685 --> 00:18:12,846
so applying global strong
consistency everywhere creates

256
00:18:12,945 --> 00:18:14,804
unnecessary performance overhead.

257
00:18:15,225 --> 00:18:18,885
So instead, organization should
apply selective consistency.

258
00:18:20,145 --> 00:18:24,044
strong consistency may only be
required for, financial transactions,

259
00:18:24,145 --> 00:18:26,345
purchase attribution or deduplication.

260
00:18:27,105 --> 00:18:31,024
Eventual consistency may be okay
for behavioral streams like click

261
00:18:31,086 --> 00:18:33,024
tracking and audience scoring.

262
00:18:35,425 --> 00:18:38,625
causal consistency is useful
where ordering matters, such

263
00:18:38,705 --> 00:18:42,304
as session stitchi-stitching
or funnel reconstruction.

264
00:18:43,745 --> 00:18:46,985
but, full global
synchronization is not required.

265
00:18:47,044 --> 00:18:50,685
So this selective approach
allows us to balance correctness,

266
00:18:50,804 --> 00:18:52,946
latency, and also throughput

267
00:18:56,609 --> 00:18:59,569
cost optimization is,
another major concern.

268
00:19:00,250 --> 00:19:04,750
Real-time systems, become expensive
if cost is not treated as operational

269
00:19:04,809 --> 00:19:06,329
metric right from the beginning.

270
00:19:07,428 --> 00:19:11,928
at the infrastructure level, spot
or preemptible instances can reduce

271
00:19:11,989 --> 00:19:16,349
costs for batch workloads where
interruption is okay, acceptable.

272
00:19:17,069 --> 00:19:22,329
At the query level, result caching,
caching materialized views and

273
00:19:22,408 --> 00:19:26,149
automated query controls can
prevent expensive ad hoc queries.

274
00:19:27,009 --> 00:19:31,990
at the data level, tiered storage policies
can move older or less frequently accessed

275
00:19:32,049 --> 00:19:35,849
data from high-performance storage
to lower cost storage automatically.

276
00:19:37,330 --> 00:19:41,729
in real-time architecture, cost
observability should sit beside,

277
00:19:41,970 --> 00:19:43,949
performance observability.

278
00:19:44,009 --> 00:19:46,490
You cannot optimize, what you cannot see

279
00:19:49,845 --> 00:19:53,505
privacy is also becoming very
central to marketing analytics.

280
00:19:54,585 --> 00:19:58,505
federated learning,
offers one path forward.

281
00:19:58,885 --> 00:20:01,885
So instead of moving raw customer
data into a central system,

282
00:20:02,425 --> 00:20:03,765
models can be trained locally,

283
00:20:06,625 --> 00:20:08,985
in a browser or within
a partner environment.

284
00:20:09,346 --> 00:20:13,145
Only model updates or gradients
are shared with central aggregator.

285
00:20:14,965 --> 00:20:21,526
This, enables us some use cases such
as, cross-publisher audience modeling,

286
00:20:21,745 --> 00:20:27,085
collaborative filtering, and on-device
per-personalization while reducing

287
00:20:27,125 --> 00:20:29,325
the need to share raw user-level data.

288
00:20:30,245 --> 00:20:34,166
So how should organizations
implement this?

289
00:20:34,945 --> 00:20:36,505
there are three broad paths.

290
00:20:36,545 --> 00:20:40,225
The first is complete
cloud-native transformation.

291
00:20:41,105 --> 00:20:45,506
this means starting fresh with
event-dri-driven architecture,

292
00:20:45,705 --> 00:20:50,065
CI/CD, managed infrastructure, and
cloud-native services from the beginning.

293
00:20:50,785 --> 00:20:54,885
this gives the most coherent long-term
architecture but is usually only best

294
00:20:54,945 --> 00:20:56,785
suited for new platform initiatives.

295
00:20:57,726 --> 00:20:59,425
The second is hybrid migration.

296
00:20:59,445 --> 00:21:01,425
This is where enterprises operate today.

297
00:21:02,205 --> 00:21:06,925
Stable workloads remain in, on batch
pipelines, while latency-sensitive

298
00:21:06,985 --> 00:21:08,245
use cases move to streaming.

299
00:21:09,406 --> 00:21:14,145
This will allow the… This
approach allows the teams to

300
00:21:14,205 --> 00:21:16,045
build expertise incrementally.

301
00:21:17,705 --> 00:21:19,905
The third is incremental modernization.

302
00:21:19,965 --> 00:21:23,885
Organizations introduce cloud-native
components into an existing on-prem

303
00:21:23,945 --> 00:21:27,025
architecture without the full migration.

304
00:21:28,125 --> 00:21:34,145
this minimizes disruption, but the batch
bottleneck often remains at the boundary

305
00:21:37,406 --> 00:21:40,406
So from production deployments,
few lessons are clear.

306
00:21:41,026 --> 00:21:44,386
Infrastructure as code
should be used from day one.

307
00:21:45,366 --> 00:21:50,186
Manual provisioning creates
inconsistency and makes recovery harder.

308
00:21:51,006 --> 00:21:54,946
Data quality infrastructure must
be built before analytic models,

309
00:21:56,106 --> 00:22:00,506
because in real-time systems, bad
data pro-propagates instantly.

310
00:22:01,846 --> 00:22:05,156
Stream processing should be
containerized, monitored, and

311
00:22:05,186 --> 00:22:06,886
supported by automatic rollback.

312
00:22:07,566 --> 00:22:10,986
Schema registries with compatibility
checks are essential to prevent

313
00:22:11,246 --> 00:22:12,686
silent upstream breakage.

314
00:22:13,126 --> 00:22:17,166
And finally, team must stress test
well beyond expected peak load.

315
00:22:17,746 --> 00:22:22,386
Many streaming failure models
only appear under pressure.

316
00:22:25,226 --> 00:22:29,786
so to conclude, cloud-native
data architecture and Data DevOps

317
00:22:29,846 --> 00:22:32,926
together represent a qualitative
shift in marketing analytics.

318
00:22:33,386 --> 00:22:35,926
This is not simply faster
version of yesterday's batch

319
00:22:36,026 --> 00:22:38,186
processing, batch reporting.

320
00:22:38,326 --> 00:22:40,676
It is a different
operational model completely.

321
00:22:41,446 --> 00:22:44,366
It requires deliberate data
foundation using lakes,

322
00:22:44,466 --> 00:22:46,766
warehouses, and lakehouse patterns.

323
00:22:46,826 --> 00:22:51,046
It requires real-time indexing strategy
built for dynamic segmentation.

324
00:22:51,566 --> 00:22:57,666
It requires mature CI/CD for
schema, pipelines, and models.

325
00:22:58,306 --> 00:23:02,026
And it requires operational
discipline around observability,

326
00:23:02,166 --> 00:23:04,046
consistency, privacy, and cost.

327
00:23:04,746 --> 00:23:08,926
So organizations that build
reliable, scalable, high performance

328
00:23:08,986 --> 00:23:13,166
real-time analytic platforms
will operate with a fundamental

329
00:23:13,286 --> 00:23:15,806
marketing intelligence advantage.

330
00:23:16,186 --> 00:23:19,086
They will not be waiting for
overnight batch jobs to complete.

331
00:23:19,566 --> 00:23:22,486
They will be learning,
adapting, and acting while

332
00:23:22,546 --> 00:23:24,206
customer intent is still alive.

333
00:23:26,386 --> 00:23:29,746
thank you so much for, letting me present

